{
  "texts": [
    "The fibre sequence (1) may be identified with the fibre sequence(2) 𝐷 𝑑 ℎ S -→ 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S -→ 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S, since 𝑃 𝑑-1 𝑃 𝑑 ≃ 𝑃 𝑑-1 and 𝐷 𝑑 𝑃 𝑑 ≃ 𝐷 𝑑.",
    "Through the equivalence between (1) and (2) an idempotent 𝑒 of 𝑃 𝑑 ℎ S acts by 𝐷 𝑑 (𝑒) on the 𝑑-homogeneous layer and 𝑃 𝑑-1 (𝑒) on the (𝑑 -1)-excisive approximation in (2).We now examine how the idempotent 𝑒 𝑑 ∈ 𝐴 Q (𝑑) acts on the fibre sequence (2) with the goal of showing that this fibre sequence induces the desired splitting.",
    "To ease notation, we will use 𝐹 [𝑒 -1] for the inversion of the action of the idempotent 𝑒 on 𝐹, where 𝐹 is any of the three functors from (2).",
    "The idempotent 𝑒 𝑑 ∈ 𝐴 Q (𝑑) acts on 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S by zero, i.e., 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S [𝑒 -1 𝑑] ≃ 0.",
    "In particular, 𝑃 𝑑-1 ℎ S is 𝑒 𝑑 -acyclic and hence (1 -𝑒 𝑑)-local.Proof."
  ]
}